======================================================================
PART 4: BEATTY SEQUENCES — φ AND √2 PARTITIONS
======================================================================

Beatty's theorem: For irrational α > 1, define β s.t. 1/α + 1/β = 1
Then B_α = {floor(nα)} and B_β = {floor(nβ)} partition Z+

For α = φ²: β = φ²/(φ²-1) = φ²·φ/(φ+1)·... = φ²·(φ-1) = φ
Wait, 1/φ² + 1/β = 1 ⟹ β = φ²/(φ²-1) = (3+√5)/2 / ((1+√5)/2)
= 1.618034
1/α + 1/β = 1.000000

For α = φ = 1.618034, β = φ² = 2.618034:
  1/φ + 1/φ² = 1.000000 = 1 ✓

B_φ  = [1, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 11, 12, 14, 16, 17, 19, 21, 22, 24, 25, 27, 29, 30]
B_φ² = [2, 5, 7, 10, 13, 15, 18, 20, 23, 26, 28, 31, 34, 36, 39, 41, 44, 47, 49]

Connection to tournament: for prime p, the Interval set is {1,...,m}
Does this relate to Beatty sequences?

  p=7: S_int = [1, 2, 3]
    B_φ mod p = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6]... (first 5 elements)
    Overlap |S_int ∩ B_φ mod p| = 3/3

  p=11: S_int = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    B_φ mod p = [0, 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8]... (first 7 elements)
    Overlap |S_int ∩ B_φ mod p| = 4/5

